        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/650695-reagan-ramsey?shelf=business-books">business-books</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer527959015" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9415441927483810255">i liked that they focused on companies that have made it long term in this book. it demonstrates that great companies aren&apos;t solely built on an idea or market timing; but on great systems, having a vision and mission that is higher than money (for real, not just something you put on a plaque somewhere), and creating a tight, consistent culture...so that it becomes apparent very quickly whether or not someone is a fit. <br/>I actually took their advice and spent some time thinking about what my missio</span>
  <span id="freeText9415441927483810255" style="display:none">i liked that they focused on companies that have made it long term in this book. it demonstrates that great companies aren't solely built on an idea or market timing; but on great systems, having a vision and mission that is higher than money (for real, not just something you put on a plaque somewhere), and creating a tight, consistent culture...so that it becomes apparent very quickly whether or not someone is a fit. <br />I actually took their advice and spent some time thinking about what my mission would be if I never got paid for what I do. I realized that what i love about my role has nothing to do with the industry or any product (you can only get so passionate about insurance), but that I get to take something very complex and expensive and make it approachable to people. Financial rewards are important, but doing something that has real purpose is what makes those long days worth it. <br />It was a good exercise. And a book definitely worth reading. </span>
  <a data-text-id="9415441927483810255" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
