    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2423576062" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2423576062" />
    <a title="Matjaz" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/69725781-matjaz"><img alt="Matjaz" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2423576062?book_show_action=true">Mar 16, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Matjaz" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Matjaz" href="/user/show/69725781-matjaz">Matjaz</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2423576062" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5084064065319428880">The center of the book is the importance of having a core ideology. It’s a good prod into larger than life visionary companies with goals (acronym BHAG – big hairy audacious goals) set 10-30 years in the future. Some passages are very good, some are encouraging the insane hyper capitalism that will one day doom us all. But as much as I was prone to cynical reading the book did manage to spark some business passion and curiosity. I must admit that it does a great job at motivating and doesn’t car</span>
  <span id="freeText5084064065319428880" style="display:none">The center of the book is the importance of having a core ideology. It’s a good prod into larger than life visionary companies with goals (acronym BHAG – big hairy audacious goals) set 10-30 years in the future. Some passages are very good, some are encouraging the insane hyper capitalism that will one day doom us all. But as much as I was prone to cynical reading the book did manage to spark some business passion and curiosity. I must admit that it does a great job at motivating and doesn’t care if it’s right or not.<br />Also I have to applaud the research that went into this project. There are various appendixes on methods, problems and obstacles during their research and further useful information and collected data on companies in the book. There is a FAQ as well, for both CEOs and non-CEOs. <br /><br />I think it’s a good inspirational pocket guide book if you’re ready for business and aren’t afraid to take it up another level but also a good insight into what makes these massive corporations tick.<br /><br />p.s. it's almost uncanny how Bezos incorporated this work into Amazon. Collins mentions that they didn't want to write the book as a step-by-step guide but Bezos took it to heart word for word and somehow made it work. I recommend the book The Everything Store by Brad Stone before reading Build to Last. It's an interesting experience.<br /><br />Light 4/5</span>
  <a data-text-id="5084064065319428880" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


